THE MOUNTAIN'S CROWN
A Chronicle of the Skyrim Wardens

PART I: THE CAMP AT KYNESGROVE
The Night After
The fire crackled, a small point of defiant light against the immense darkness pressing in from all sides. The sounds from the ruined village were a low, constant murmurΓÇöthe quiet weeping of survivors, the creak of makeshift shelters being erected, the whispered prayers to gods who may no longer be listening.
Krusp Fanck was gone. The legendary warrior who had fought beside them against a dragon, who had proved himself in blood and fire, had looked into their souls and found them wanting. His final words hung in the air like an executioner's blade: "If I hear of you preying on the innocent, I will hunt you down."
The Obsidian LanternsΓÇönow Skyrim's Wardens, chartered by a dead kingΓÇösat in tense, hollow silence. The victory against Sahloknir felt meaningless. They had saved Kynesgrove from one monster, but in Krusp's eyes, they were simply different monsters wearing heroes' masks.
Davinia stared into the flames, one hand unconsciously touching the crown of ice that had settled around her brow. The Pale Lady's gift. Ismara's curse. She could feel it even now, whispering to her about preservation, about protecting the fragile things she loved by making them hard, by making them cold, by making them safe from a world that burned everything it touched.
Beside her, Danica shifted closer, seeking warmth. The priestess had been quiet since Krusp's departure, her usual brightness dimmed by the weight of his accusations. When she reached for Davinia's hand, the warrior felt the Crown pulseΓÇö
Softness is death. Warmth is decay.
Davinia pulled her hand away, just slightly, just enough. She saw the hurt flash across Danica's face before the priestess masked it with understanding. The Crown settled, satisfied.
"I'm sorry," Davinia whispered. "I'm just... cold."
"I know," Danica said softly. She pulled her own cloak tighter and gave Davinia a small, sad smile. "I'll keep the fire going."
Across the circle, Kyboah sat examining his ruined gloves in the firelight. The grey ceramic had cracked like shattered pottery, spiderweb fractures spreading across the knuckles where the runes had burned out. His hands still ached with a deep, bone-grinding pain that no amount of healing magic could touch. The vision of the Titan haunted himΓÇöthe hammer falling, the pressure testing his very structure, the terrible certainty that he was carrying a weapon pointed at himself.
He looked up and caught Saijah watching him. The Bosmer's eyes were troubled, her connection to Kynareth's Green making her acutely sensitive to the wrongness radiating from his cursed equipment. She opened her mouth as if to speak, then closed it again. What could she say? That she could feel the gloves dying? That they smelled like burning soul-energy and desperate mathematics? That sitting next to him felt like sitting next to a ticking clock counting down to an explosion she couldn't prevent?
Instead, she moved closer to Old Bjorn, who sat by the horses with his weathered face drawn and pale. The old carter had been quiet since the dragon's death, one hand pressed occasionally to his chest as if nursing some deep internal ache. Saijah settled beside him, drawing comfort from his solid, mortal presence. Unlike her companionsΓÇöthe vampires, the cursed warrior, the woman in the dead queen's crownΓÇöBjorn was just a man. Complicated, perhaps hiding secrets of his own, but fundamentally human.
"You alright, lass?" Bjorn asked quietly.
"I don't know," Saijah admitted. "Everything feels... wrong. Like the world is rotting from the inside and we're the only ones who can smell it."
Bjorn grunted. "Aye. But we're still here. Still breathing. That counts for something."
On the far side of the fire, Orion sat alone, fingers absently turning the heavy silver ring on his finger. Valerius's ring. The mark of ownership, the beacon that proclaimed him property of the Cyrodiil Order. He could feel it sometimesΓÇöa cold pressure behind his eyes, the sensation of being observed, of having his master listen through his ears to every conversation, every plan, every moment of vulnerability.
He'd put it on immediately when he found it in his pack. The choice had been instinctive, almost eager. Protection. Recognition. A place in the hierarchy. But now, sitting in the firelight with Krusp's condemnation still echoing in his mind, he wondered if the legendary warrior had been right.
Monsters wearing heroes' masks.
Alfonso had disappeared into the ruins shortly after Krusp left, claiming he needed air. He hadn't returned. Orion knew what his fellow vampire was doingΓÇöhunting, feeding, indulging the appetites that Valerius had cultivated in him. Creating more plague ghouls in the dark, spreading Peryite's gift through the wounded and dying while the Stormcloaks' attention was elsewhere.
They were becoming what Krusp had named them. And Orion didn't know if he had the strengthΓÇöor the desireΓÇöto fight it.
In the quiet darkness, Orion pulled out his Primer of Resonant FrequenciesΓÇöthe study guide Dean Giraud had sent him from the Bards College. He flipped to Partition Nine, the section on Tonal Architecture and the physics of violence.
The dragon fight. Sahloknir. The memory was still vividΓÇöthe bone-shaking roar, the screech of metal on scale, the visceral crunch when Kyboah's impossible punch had shattered the dragon's ribs. That sound. That terrible, beautiful sound of entropy made manifest, of force overwhelming structure.
He began to write, translating combat into music theory, violence into harmonic notation. The Movement of Entropy took shape on the pageΓÇöa composition built on dissonance and resolution, on the mathematical certainty that all things break when sufficient pressure is applied.
When he finished, the spell hummed with potential. He could feel itΓÇöthe ability to weaken armor, to reduce an enemy's defenses, to make the hard things brittle. A song of destruction, codified and controlled.
He closed the book and tucked it away, one more secret added to the growing collection.

Bjorn's Oath
Old Bjorn approached the fire, his weathered face cast in sharp relief by the flames. He'd been tending to his horses and cart, deliberately giving them space, but he'd been listening.
"He's wrong," Bjorn said quietly.
The simple declaration cut through the heavy silence. Davinia looked up, startled. The old man met her eyes steadily.
"Krusp Fanck is a good man," Bjorn continued. "A great warrior. But he's wrong about you. I've watched you since Winterhold. You didn't have to come to Kynesgrove. You didn't have to face that dragon. You didn't have to risk your lives for people you'd never met. But you did."
He settled himself by the fire, pulling a blanket around his shoulders.
"The LanternsΓÇöit's a good dream. Maybe the only one this kingdom has left. High King Torygg saw something in you, and I see it too. You're not perfect. None of us are. But you're trying to do right by a world that's falling apart, and that's more than most can say."
He poked at the fire with a stick, sending sparks spiraling into the night.
"I'm staying. I'm with you. Whatever comes next, we face it together."
The words settled over the camp like a benediction. Danica's eyes shone with tears. Saijah reached out to squeeze Bjorn's weathered hand. Even Kyboah looked up from his broken gloves with something like gratitude in his eyes.
Only Davinia seemed unconvinced. She stared at the old carter with a mixture of appreciation and deep concern.
"Why?" she asked. "After everything Krusp said. After seeing what we... what some of us have become. Why would you stay?"
Bjorn was quiet for a long moment. His hand moved unconsciously to his chest again, pressing against whatever ache lived there. When he spoke, his voice was very soft.
"Because I think we're all carrying something we don't understand. And maybe... maybe we need each other to bear the weight."
He didn't elaborate. But in the firelight, his eyes held a fear that matched their own.

The Morning After
Dawn broke grey and cold over Kynesgrove. The party woke to the sound of hoofbeats and marching feet approaching from the east.
The Stormcloaks had arrived.
Captain Valdmar led a column of supply wagons and soldiers wearing the blue and grey of the rebellion. They weren't moving like a war partyΓÇöthey were moving like a relief force, and the soldiers were laughing, celebrating, their spirits impossibly high given the devastation surrounding them.
Valdmar spotted the party's campfire and made a direct approach, flanked by veterans whose hands rested casually on their weapons. Professional assessment, not aggression, but the message was clear: identify yourselves.
"Evening," Valdmar said, his weathered face studying each of them with a veteran's eye. "You're not locals, and you're better geared than most sellswords I've seen. You've got the look of people who've seen real combat."
His eyes scanned their weapons, their armor, noting the quality and wear patterns. He stopped a respectful distance from the fire.
"I'm Captain Valdmar, Third Regiment, Windhelm garrison. I'm here on Jarl Ulfric's authority to render aid to Kynesgrove." He paused, weight settling behind the words. "On the orders of the true High King of Skyrim."
The party exchanged glances. True High King. Which meantΓÇö
"Who are you," Valdmar continued, watching their reactions carefully, "and what's your business in his lands on the day history is made?"
Davinia's mind raced. The day history is made. Torygg. Something had happened to Torygg. She fought to keep her expression neutral, reaching for the Legion training that had taught her to maintain composure under interrogation.
"We're travelers," she said carefully. "We saw the smoke, heard the screaming. We helped where we could."
Valdmar's eyes narrowed slightly. "Travelers don't wear that quality of steel. And they don't survive dragon attacks." He gestured toward the massive skeleton on the hill, clearly visible in the morning light. "That's your work, isn't it?"
Kyboah stepped forward, his massive frame and confident bearing drawing Valdmar's attention. The Khajiit understood soldiersΓÇöyou didn't deflect with people like the Captain, you gave them enough truth to satisfy their professional curiosity.
"Yes," Kyboah said simply. "We killed it. The cultists raised it, we put it down. The people here can confirm."
Valdmar's expression shiftedΓÇösurprise, then something like respect. "Dragon-slayers. Well." He seemed to reassess them entirely. "Then you've done Skyrim a great service. These people owe you their lives."
He gestured to his men, who visibly relaxed. "I won't keep you then. You're welcome to resupply from our wagons if you need." He started to turn, then paused. "You haven't heard the news from Solitude, have you?"
Davinia's stomach dropped. "No. What happened?"
Valdmar smiledΓÇönot cruel, but triumphant. "Ulfric Stormcloak challenged High King Torygg to single combat this morning. In the Blue Palace, in front of the entire court. The old wayΓÇöspeak with steel, or be silent."
The world seemed to tilt.
"Torygg accepted. He had toΓÇörefusing would have proven him a coward. The duel lasted less than a minute. Ulfric used the Voice. The Thu'um. They say you could hear it from the docks."
Valdmar's smile widened. "When it was over, Torygg was no longer fit to rule. Ulfric is High King now, by right of combat and the old traditions. The Empire can cry 'murder' all they want, but Nord law is clear."
He looked at each of them in turn. "The war's begun. And we're on the winning side."
Davinia couldn't breathe. Torygg. Dead. The king who had chartered them, who had believed in Skyrim's heroes, who had created the Wardens to save the province from itselfΓÇömurdered in his own throne room while they were fighting a dragon in the wilderness.
Danica grabbed her arm, steadying her. The priestess's face was pale, but her grip was strong.
"Thank you for the news, Captain," Davinia managed. Her voice sounded distant to her own ears. "We'll... we'll consider your offer."
Valdmar nodded and moved away, already shouting orders to his men about setting up the relief tents. The Stormcloaks flowed past their camp, efficient and professional, bringing aid to the grateful survivors.
The Wardens sat in stunned silence.
"Our charter," Saijah said quietly. "It was issued by Torygg. If he's deadΓÇö"
"Then we're operating under a dead king's authority in a kingdom that no longer recognizes it," Kyboah finished. He looked at Davinia. "What do we do?"
Davinia stared into the dying embers of their fire. The Crown of the Pale Lady felt heavy on her brow, whispering about the futility of warm things, about how all kingdoms fall to ice eventually.
"We do what we came here to do," she said finally. "Torygg chartered us to protect Skyrim from supernatural threats. That mission doesn't change just because the king is dead."
She looked at each of them in turnΓÇöthe cursed warrior, the connected druid, the vampires, the priestess, the loyal carter.
"The dragons are still waking. The cults are still operating. The province still needs defending. So we defend it."

Alfonso's Transaction
While the others processed the news and packed their gear, Alfonso drifted toward the Stormcloak medical tent with a predator's focus.
The horses. The Stormcloaks had brought supply horses, and one of themΓÇöa sturdy grey mareΓÇöhad developed riding sores from the hard journey. The wounds were infected, weeping that perfect mixture of blood and pus that made Alfonso's mouth water with anticipation.
But he couldn't just attack it. Not here, not in the middle of a military camp. He needed a transaction. A legitimate purchase that would let him take the animal away from prying eyes.
He found the medicΓÇöa tired Nord woman organizing suppliesΓÇöand approached with his most concerned expression.
"Excuse me," Alfonso said softly. "I'm a restoration mage. I couldn't help but notice your grey mare has developed some concerning wounds."
The medic looked up, exhausted. "Mable? Yes, poor thing. The harness rubbed her raw on the journey. We've been treating it, butΓÇö"
"Those aren't riding sores," Alfonso interrupted gently. "That's plague-rot. Early stage, but unmistakable. I've seen it before." He shook his head sadly. "If it spreads to your other animals, you'll lose the entire string within a week."
The medic's face went pale. "Plague? But we... we can't afford to loseΓÇö"
"She needs to be put down," Alfonso said firmly. "Immediately. Before the infection spreads." He reached into his coin purse, counting out gold pieces. "I'll give you five hundred gold for her. I'll take her away from camp, dispose of the body properly, ensure there's no contamination."
Five hundred gold. For a sick horse they'd have to kill anyway. The medic hesitated only a moment before taking the money.
"Thank you," she said, relief evident in her voice. "You're probably saving the whole column. She's yours."
Alfonso led Mable away from the camp, deeper into the ruins of Kynesgrove where the shadows were thick and no one was watching. The mare followed docilely, unaware of her fate.
In a collapsed building far from prying eyes, Alfonso knelt beside the horse. His fingers found the infected sores, and he pressed his lips to the weeping wounds. The taste was exquisiteΓÇöhot blood mixed with the sharp, complex tang of active infection. Peryite's gift sang in his veins, recognizing the beautiful rot, encouraging him to partake.
He fed carefully at first, savoring each sore, drinking the infected fluid like fine wine. The mare's breathing grew labored, but she didn't struggle. Perhaps some part of her understood this was mercy.
When the sores were drained clean, Alfonso moved to her throat. The blood was still warm, still vital, and he drank deeply until the mare's heartbeat stuttered and stopped.
Then came the feast.
Namira's hunger rose in him like a tide, and Alfonso gave himself to it completely. Flesh and blood and bone, consumed methodically, efficiently, the way a craftsman approaches his work. He ate until nothing remained but stained earth and the memory of satisfaction.
When he returned to camp an hour later, his clothes were clean, his expression serene. He'd fed fully on both his patrons' giftsΓÇöPeryite's corruption and Namira's consumption. The hunger was sated, at least for now.
No one asked where he'd been. They were learning not to.

The Council
When the party gathered to discuss their next move, Bjorn spread a map across a flat stone and looked at them grimly.
"Let's talk logistics," he said. "Torygg is dead. That stipend Falk Firebeard handed you? That came from the King's personal treasury. With Torygg gone, Jarl Elisif controls those vaults now, and she's going to be too busy holding onto her throne to worry about paying freelance monster hunters."
He pointed at the Imperial seal on his own travel papers. "However, my contract for this cart and these horses was filed with the Imperial Logistics Office in Solitude. General Tullius pays his bills. I'm still a civilian contractor as far as the supply chain is concerned. You might be broke, but you've still got wheels, and you've still got me."
Davinia felt a surge of gratitude toward the old man. "Thank you, Bjorn. That's... that's more than we deserve."
"You've earned it," Bjorn said gruffly. He turned back to the map. "But we have a bigger problem. While I was watering the horses near the Stormcloak wagons, I picked up some intelligence. Three things are happening right now, and all of them are urgent."
He pointed to locations on the map as he spoke.
"First: Korvanjund. The soldiers say Galmar Stone-Fist is taking a column to raid an old tomb. They're after the Jagged CrownΓÇöan ancient symbol of Nordic kingship. If Ulfric gets that crown, his claim to the throne becomes a lot more legitimate. But Korvanjund is crawling with Draugr, and if your dragon cult is active there..."
"Second: The Eldergleam Sanctuary. I saw a priestess of Kynareth on the road yesterday. She was running from the sanctuary, terrified. Said the sacred tree is dying, bleeding black sap. Pilgrims have gone missing. Sound familiar?"
Saijah's breath caught. The corruption from Thornheart Grove, spreading to one of Kynareth's holiest sites.
"Third: Ansilvund and Stony Creek. A mining camp went dark two days ago. They found one survivor. He said Draugr came out of the ruins and dragged people back inside. Alive. Draugr don't take prisoners."
Bjorn looked at each of them. "Three urgent crises. We can't hit all of them. Make the call."
The party discussed for nearly an hour. Kyboah argued for his own crisisΓÇöfinding the Master Smith to fix his gloves before the curse killed himΓÇöbut the others pointed out that none of the current options led directly north toward Winterhold. Eventually, he conceded.
The choice came down to the Crown or the Sanctuary.
"If we let Galmar get the Jagged Crown," Davinia said slowly, "Ulfric's legitimacy strengthens. The civil war gets worse. But if we can reach it first, maybe we can deny him that symbol. Maybe even get it to Elisif."
"The Eldergleam is dying right now," Saijah countered. "Every hour we delay, the corruption spreads."
"The miners at Stony Creek are dying right now too," Danica added quietly.
The weight of impossible choices settled over them. Finally, Davinia made the decision.
"We go to Korvanjund. The civil war is tearing this province apart, and that crown could tip the balance. We can't save everyone, but we can try to stop things from getting worse."
She looked at Saijah. "I'm sorry. I know the Eldergleam matters to you. ButΓÇö"
"I understand," Saijah said, though her voice was tight with suppressed grief. "The needs of many."
Bjorn nodded and began packing the map. "Korvanjund it is. Two days' travel if the weather holds."

PART II: THE ROAD TO KORVANJUND
The Wolf on the Road
The journey to Korvanjund took them through increasingly hostile terrain. The smell of sulfur and marshland faded, replaced by the biting scent of ice and pine resin. The road climbed steadily upward into the mountains, the dirt turning to hard-packed permafrost.
On the second day, as they navigated a narrow canyon pass, a massive pine trunk crashed down from the ridge above. It slammed into the road twenty feet ahead of the cart, blocking their path completely.
Bjorn hauled on the reins, bringing the horses to a panicked halt. The party reached for weaponsΓÇö
A single figure leaped from the ridge. She landed on the fallen trunk with a ground-shaking thud that cracked the bark, and straightened to her full, imposing height.
She was Nord, built like the mountains themselves, wearing custom steel plate hammered and scarred by a hundred battles. Her hair was thick and braided, split perfectly down the middle: one side blood-red, the other spun gold. A battleaxe the size of a man rested casually on her shoulder.
She stared at the party with wide, delighted eyes.
"Well now!" she boomed, her voice echoing off the canyon walls. "The cart matches the description. The gear matches the rumors. And the smell..." She sniffed deeply. "Ozone. Old magic. Dragon blood. It's you."
She hopped down from the log and walked toward them with easy confidence.
"I'm Ylva. They call me the Cleaver. I tracked those cultists at Kynesgrove for three weeksΓÇöplanned to mount their heads on my wall. But when I arrived, the dragon lay dead. The cultists were ash." She looked directly at Kyboah. "You killed a god. You cleared my board. I've hunted my whole life, but I've never seen a kill like that."
She stopped a few feet from the cart and planted her axe in the snow.
"I want in. I want to run with this pack. But I know who you areΓÇöthe Wardens. You take only the strong." She unbuckled her gauntlets and dropped them in the snow, raising her bare fists. "I must prove I belong."
She pointed at Kyboah. "You. Whiskers. You hit that dragon hard enough to make the earth shake. I need to know if I can stand next to you. One round. No weapons. Let's go."
Kyboah looked at his broken gloves, then at the enthusiastic warrior-woman challenging him. He sighed and climbed down from the cart.
"Fine. But I'm going easy on you. These aren't working right."
Ylva's grin widened. "We'll see about that."
The fight was brief but fierce. Ylva moved with the practiced efficiency of someone who'd survived a hundred brawls, her strikes economical and brutal. Kyboah, hampered by his damaged gloves and the constant pain they caused, fought defensively, testing her skill rather than trying to overpower her.
They traded blows for several minutes before Kyboah managed to sweep her legs and pin her in the snow. She laughed, breathless and exhilarated.
"See? That's what I mean! That control! I can learn from you!" She accepted his hand to pull herself up. "Please. Let me watch your back. I won't let you down."
Davinia stepped forward. "You said you tracked the cultists. What do you know about them?"
"Dragon worshippers," Ylva said, brushing snow from her armor. "They've been moving through Eastmarch for months. I've been hunting them, but they're organized. Coordinated. They're building toward something big."
She looked at the party with open admiration. "You stopped them at Kynesgrove. You killed their god. That makes you the most dangerous thing in Skyrim right now. And I want to be part of that."
Davinia exchanged glances with the others. They were already carrying secretsΓÇövampires, curses, divine corruption. Adding a boisterous Nord warrior to the mix seemed almost refreshingly normal.
"Alright," Davinia said finally. "Welcome to the Wardens, Ylva the Cleaver."
Ylva whooped and retrieved her axe, vaulting onto the cart with infectious enthusiasm.

The Road Fellowship
As the cart rolled onward, Ylva settled in among them like she'd always been there. She sat next to Kyboah initially, still flushed from their sparring match, and bombarded them with questions about the dragon fight.
"Who landed the killing blow? Was it you, big guy? Or did the archer get a lucky shot in the eye? Tell me everything!"
Kyboah found himself describing the battle despite his usual reticence. There was something disarming about Ylva's genuine enthusiasm. She listened with rapt attention, occasionally interrupting with excited exclamations.
When the story was done, she turned to the others. "And the rest of you? What's your specialty?"
Saijah explained her archery and connection to Kynareth. Davinia spoke carefully about her tactical training and magical abilities, avoiding mention of the Crown. Danica described her healing work with the temple. Orion demonstrated his war horn's capabilities.
Alfonso remained quiet, watching Ylva with hooded eyes. The Nord woman's vitality, her sheer life-force, was almost painful to be near. She radiated health and warmth in a way that made his undead nature feel like a cold, hollow thing by comparison.
But Ylva seemed drawn to him specifically. She moved to sit beside him after the initial round of introductions, studying his face with open curiosity.
"You're quiet," she observed. "Not shy though. Calculating. I like that." She leaned closer, sniffing. "You smell interesting. Like... old meat? Aging venison?"
Alfonso tensed, but Ylva seemed more intrigued than repulsed.
"I've met vampires before," she continued casually. "Hunted a nest in Morthal last year. They didn't smell like you though. You're something different."
The cart went very quiet. Ylva looked around at their shocked faces and laughed.
"What? You think I can't tell? I've been tracking things through the wilderness since I was six years old. I know what's human and what's not." She shrugged. "Doesn't bother me. You killed a dragon. That earns you some latitude."
She looked at Orion. "You too, bard. Same scent, but... fresher? Newer? How long have you been undead?"
Orion's hand moved instinctively to his sword. "Is this going to be a problem?"
"Only if you make it one," Ylva said cheerfully. "I don't care what you are. I care what you do. And what you did was save Kynesgrove. So we're good."
She turned back to Alfonso. "Besides, I've done worse things than befriend a vampire. At least you have an excuse for your appetites."
The comment hung in the air, loaded with implication. Kyboah caught it immediatelyΓÇöhis suspicions about Ylva crystallizing into near-certainty. She was a werewolf. Had to be. The strength, the tracking ability, the casual acceptance of monstrous nature.
He almost asked her directly, but something held him back. She wasn't hiding it, not really. Just not advertising it either. And if she was comfortable with their secrets, maybe they could be comfortable with hers.
The revelation that Ylva knew and didn't care about the vampires seemed to lift a weight from the group. Conversation flowed more naturally after that, though they were still careful about specifics.
When they made camp that evening, Ylva challenged Alfonso to a sparring match. The vampire accepted, curious about this strange, vital woman who seemed utterly unafraid of him.
She beat him unconscious. Twice.
The first time, she'd used a clever feint that exploited his slower-than-mortal reflexes. The second time was pure powerΓÇöa devastating right hook that his defensive magics couldn't fully absorb.
Both times, she helped him up afterward with a cheerful grin and genuine respect in her eyes. And both times, Alfonso found himself oddly attracted to the experience. Not just the violence, but the competence. The absolute confidence she displayed in her own physical dominance.
The other party members watched with varying degrees of disgustΓÇöparticularly when Alfonso seemed almost pleased by the defeatsΓÇöbut no one commented directly.
He was starting to understand why Valerius valued strength so highly. There was something intoxicating about being near someone so utterly, vibrantly alive.

The Bandit Interlude
On the final approach to Korvanjund, Ylva suddenly tensed, sniffing the air.
"Bandits," she said quietly. "Three of them. Downwind, about half a mile east. They've been watching the road."
The party exchanged glances. Davinia made the call. "Let's clear them out before they can report our movements to anyone else."
The bandits never stood a chance. The Wardens descended on their camp like a force of natureΓÇöKyboah and Ylva providing overwhelming physical force, Saijah's arrows finding throats with surgical precision, Alfonso's magic freezing one bandit in place for Orion to execute.
Within minutes, two were dead and one was on his knees, begging.
"Please! Please don'tΓÇöI have a family in Riften, I was just trying toΓÇö"
Alfonso stepped forward, and the man's pleas turned to incoherent terror as he recognized what the elf was. "No, no, please don't eat me, don'tΓÇö"
Davinia raised a hand. "Stop."
She looked at the sobbing manΓÇöreally looked at him. Worn clothes. Thin frame. Desperation in his eyes. Not a career criminal, just someone who'd made bad choices when hunger and fear drove him to it.
She reached into her coin purse and pulled out twenty gold pieces. "Take this. Go to Riften. Find honest work. If I see you on this road again, I won't be merciful."
The bandit stared at the gold in disbelief, then grabbed it and ran, disappearing into the wilderness without looking back.
