Galmar laughedΓÇöa genuine, warm sound that seemed impossible in the middle of this carnage. Then another explosion hit above them, showering the command post in dust, and the general was back.
He turned to assess the rest of the party with a veteran's eye.
"A Bosmer archer. A Khajiit brawler. A mage. A blade-singer. A priestess." He gave Ylva a gruff nod. "And the Cleaver. You've brought a rough-looking company, Davinia. But if you vouch for them, I'll use them."
He slammed his fist onto a charcoal map sketched on a crate.
"We're bleeding for every inch. That door is the only way in, but the mages hold the high balcony directly above it. Every time I mass a line to charge the stairs, they drop a wall of fire. I've lost thirty men trying to reach the first step."
He gestured at the cliffs. "I tried to be clever. Sent two squads up the west cliff to flank them. They vanished. No bodies, just... gone."
Galmar looked at Davinia with exhausted determination. "I can keep their attention on the stairs. Act as the anvil. But I cannot breach that door while the artillery is active. If you and your specialists can do anything to stop that fire, do it. Otherwise, get clear. I'm ordering the next charge in five minutes."

The Flank
The party chose the hidden pathΓÇöthe goat trail that wound up the far left cliff face, completely concealed from the main temple entrance. It was treacherous, barely ten feet wide, with a sheer mountain wall to the left and a hundred-twenty-foot drop to the right.
They moved carefully, weapons ready, until they rounded a blind corner and found the blockade.
Two massive Frost Atronachs blocked the narrow path completely, jagged beings of living ice that filled the trail from wall to cliff-edge. Around their feet stood the missing scoutsΓÇöStormcloak soldiers, dead but animate, their eyes empty and their movements jerky.
