His gem-eyes swept across the assembled force, analyzing, categorizing. When they landed on the Wardens, he paused.
"Interesting variables," he murmured, almost to himself. His gaze fell on Kyboah. "The Maker's Mark. A self-contained kinetic loop. Hjolmar was busy after I went to sleep."
He looked at Alfonso, and something like a smile crossed his ruined face. "A fascinating pathogen. Peryite's orderly rot, built onto Bal's chaotic gift. Your thralls stink of potential."
His eyes moved to Saijah. "The Hawk's breath. Divine spark. Anomaly."
To Orion and Davinia. "Two ghosts. One clinging to mortal sounds, the other wearing a Queen's crown like common jewelry."
He reached over his shoulder. With a wet clack, he twisted the primary valve on the rig bolted to his spine. Green steam vented violently from his neck seals. The tubes running into his shoulders glowed angry red as combat stimulants flooded his system.
He drew a Daedric Warhammer from his backΓÇöa slab of black metal that looked less like a weapon and more like a siege engine. He rested its head on the ground, and the impact shook the entire room.
"You are statistically improbable variables. Debris. Clutter." His voice became synthesized, mechanical, final. "I will not abide contaminants in my workspace."
The party readied their weapons. Galmar and Hroki took positions at the front. Alfonso's sixteen plague ghouls spread out, creating a wall of corrupted flesh between the Orc and the living.
Ylva grinned, raising her axe. "Now this is what I joined for."
Danica gripped her staff, standing close to Davinia. The warrior squeezed her hand once, briefly, then let go.
Ulag the Breaker settled into a combat stance, his hydraulic armor hissing with pneumatic pressure.
And in the silence before the storm, before the violence and the blood and the desperate struggle for survival, the only sound was the relentless grinding of the drill still chewing into the vault door behind him.
GRIND. THUD. GRIND. THUD.

